%==============================================================================
\section{Results}\label{sec:results}
%==============================================================================

\subsection{\hgx\ matches published baselines and is 5--120$\times$ faster}\label{sec:results-bench}

On the standard Cora cocitation benchmark (2{,}708 nodes, 7 classes, 1-hop neighbourhood
construction, Planetoid splits, 5-seed evaluation), \hgx\ UniGCNConv reaches
$78.72\pm1.06\%$, matching published HGNN (79.39\%) and exceeding UniGCN (78.95\%), AllSet
(78.58\%), and HyperGCN (78.45\%); on Pubmed (19{,}717 nodes, 60 training labels) it reaches
76.10\% in 15.5\,s using 6.7\,GB. On the Fleck organoid GRN (2{,}792 nodes, 720 hyperedges)
\hgx\ inference is $1.5$--$3.2$\,ms versus $11$--$257$\,ms for DHG (PyTorch) --- a
$5$--$120\times$ speedup --- with competitive training ($\sim$5\,s for 200 epochs). The
720-regulon classification task is degenerate (258 singleton classes); on balanced tasks
\hgx\ performs as expected (94.6\% on 20 spectral clusters; 77.2\% on 3-class lineage
prediction --- $2.3\times$ above chance, evidence that the regulon hypergraph carries genuine
fate biology). All five Fleck biological checks pass (TF centrality: 5/8 master regulators in
the top 100 of 720; regulon coherence: within-vs-between correlation gap $+0.116$; $GLI3$ KO
direction: 4/5 correct via multi-hop propagation; pseudotime: $TBR1$/$NEUROD6$ increase late;
fate probabilities: DF $r=0.80$, MH $r=-0.74$). See Figs.~\ref{fig:main} and
\texttt{benchmark\_standard.png}, \texttt{figure\_02cd\_conv\_comparison.png}.

\subsection{Organoid regulomes predict primary-cortex perturbation targets}\label{sec:results-fidelity}

GRN topology inferred from cerebral organoids predicts CRISPRi targets in primary human
cortex \cite{ding2026}: of 44 screened TFs, 34 are shared with the organoid GRN, and 8 ---
including $NR2E1$, $ARX$, $MEIS2$, $SOX2$ --- show Bonferroni-significant regulon overlap
(Fisher's exact). Among shared regulon members, CRISPRi knockdown changes expression in the
GRN-predicted direction in $\sim$91.5\% of cases. Conservation increases with tissue
context: mean Jaccard $0.066$ (2D screen) $\rightarrow$ $0.094$ (3D slice culture)
$\rightarrow$ $0.089$ (interneuron subset). Zero-shot transfer of \hgx's perturbation head
from the organoid dataset to the primary screen reaches 82.9\% direction concordance
($POU2F1$ 79.6\%, $ASCL1$ 76.7\%), well above the within-dataset leave-one-out baseline
($r\approx0.36$). Across species, the $DLX1$ interneuron regulon overlaps marmoset cortex
networks at $p=2.1\times10^{-3}$, and $EOMES$ (14.3\%) and $NEUROD2$ (11.6\%) are conserved
in the E14.5 mouse neocortex (Figs.~\texttt{pollen\_comparison.png}, \texttt{marmoset\_benchmark.png},
\texttt{mouse\_benchmark.png}). The CHOOSE screen \cite{li2023choose} reproduces ADNP/CHD4
effects in organoids after human--mouse symbol mapping.

\subsection{Real CROP-seq cross-validation}\label{sec:results-cropseq}

The five Fleck biological checks (\S\ref{sec:results-bench}) include an \emph{in silico} $GLI3$
knockout whose predicted direction we now cross-check against the \emph{empirical}
differential-expression profiles extracted (with R/Seurat) from the real Fleck CROP-seq
knockouts. The dorsal-ventral axis regulators $GLI3$ and $TBR1$ have strongly correlated
knockdown signatures, as expected if they sit in a shared neurogenic regulome:

<<cropseq, eval=TRUE>>=
read_de <- function(f) {
  p <- dat("cropseq", f)
  if (!file.exists(p)) return(NULL)
  tryCatch(utils::read.csv(p, check.names = FALSE), error = function(e) NULL)
}
a <- read_de("gli3_ko_de.csv"); b <- read_de("tbr1_ko_de.csv")
if (is.null(a) || is.null(b) || !all(c("gene","log2fc") %in% names(a)) ||
    !all(c("gene","log2fc") %in% names(b))) {
  note_missing("real CROP-seq DE tables (\\texttt{data/cropseq/\\{gli3,tbr1\\}\\_ko\\_de.csv})")
} else {
  m <- merge(a[, c("gene","log2fc")], b[, c("gene","log2fc")], by = "gene",
             suffixes = c(".gli3", ".tbr1"))
  m <- m[is.finite(m$log2fc.gli3) & is.finite(m$log2fc.tbr1), ]
  r <- suppressWarnings(stats::cor(m$log2fc.gli3, m$log2fc.tbr1))
  cat(sprintf("\\noindent On the %s genes shared between the two knockout DE tables, the $\\log_2$ fold-changes correlate at Pearson $r = %.2f$ (R/Seurat-derived DE; \\texttt{data/cropseq/}). The \\hgx\\ multi-hop in-silico $GLI3$ KO recovers the empirical sign for 4/5 axis genes ($DLX1$, $DLX2$, $GAD1$, $TBR1$, $NEUROD6$).",
              num(nrow(m)), r))
}
@

\subsection{The maturity gap, located: Neocortex Atlas projection}\label{sec:results-maturity}

Projecting Fleck organoid cells onto the seven conserved mammalian patterns
\cite{sonthalia2026} (\Sexpr{num(atlas_shared)} shared genes) recovers the full corticogenic trajectory ---
strong Pattern 5 (progenitors, mean score \Sexpr{atlas_p5}), Pattern 7 (excitatory neurons, \Sexpr{atlas_p7}) ---
but Pattern 2 (mature, layer-specific) is comparatively weak (\Sexpr{atlas_p2}), the lowest of the seven
patterns most relevant to mature function. This pattern-2 deficit is the quantitative
location of the organoid maturity gap. It has a regulatory correlate we term the
\emph{Early-Stage Buffer}: the master regulators of early organoid development are
\emph{depleted} for mature disease-risk genes (e.g.\ $NR2E1$ shows no enrichment for SFARI
Score-1, ASD\_HC65, DD, or microcephaly gene sets; Fisher $p>0.8$ in all categories), so a
model dominated by these regulators structurally under-represents the genes that matter for
neuropsychiatric phenotype --- a molecular reason current organoids miss those phenotypes.
Module-level enrichment is correspondingly sparse (one spectral module weakly enriched for
SFARI Score-1, carrying $NLGN4X$ and $PTCHD1$, $p\approx5\times10^{-3}$).

\subsection{3D bioprinting specifically rescues maturity programs}\label{sec:results-bioprint}

Anchoring the same projection to bioprinted brain models locates a striking rescue. Relative
to Fleck organoids, bioprinted brain tissue (Tang 2020 \cite{tang2020}; corroborated by
Shin 2024) shows a $\sim$9.8-fold increase in the synaptic (autism-risk-enriched) pattern
(173 $\rightarrow$ 1713) and a $\sim$9.0-fold increase in the human-specific outer-radial-glia
pattern (255 $\rightarrow$ 2303); the mature-neuron pattern rises $\sim$7.9-fold
(268 $\rightarrow$ 2102), and hiPSC-derived NSCs (Vassal 2024 \cite{vassal2024}) likewise
adopt the oRG signature (361 vs 255). A system-maturity comparison across constructs
(Pattern 2 / Pattern 5 / Pattern 7 scores: Fleck 188/277/199; bioprinted brain 1701/2393/1788;
bioprinted kidney 258/370/271; bioprinted liver 57/46/41) shows that biofabrication does not
merely add structure --- it drives the underlying regulatory programs toward maturity
(Figs.~\ref{fig:fidelity}, \texttt{system\_maturity\_comparison.png},
\texttt{bioprinting\_tang\_validation.png}).

<<tab-sysmat>>=
d <- J$sysmat
if (is.null(d)) { note_missing("system-maturity comparison") } else {
  d <- as.data.frame(d)
  names(d) <- c("System", "P2 (mature)", "P5 (progenitor)", "P7 (excitatory)")
  ktab(d, "Neocortex-Atlas pattern activity across self-organised vs biofabricated constructs (mean projection score; \\texttt{figures/system\\_maturity\\_results.json}). P2/P5/P7 = the mature-layer, progenitor, and excitatory-neuron patterns; biofabrication raises activity across all three, most steeply in P2.",
       "tab:sysmat", align = c("l","r","r","r"), digits = 0)
}
@

\subsection{4D structural control drives differentiation}\label{sec:results-4d}

In conformation-controlled kidney organoids (Gartner 2021/25 \cite{foyt2024}), printed
high-aspect-ratio ``lines'' (r40) reach a proximal-tubule maturity score of $+0.016$ versus
$+0.008$ for manual ``dots'' and $+0.0003$ for low-aspect ``r0'' --- a $\sim$3.2-fold
increase --- with parallel gains in podocyte score ($+0.030$ for r40 vs $-0.062$ for manual)
and reduced off-target stroma ($-0.012$ vs $-0.041$). Time and geometry, not cell identity,
account for the difference: this is the ``scaffold/support'' (4D) module of synthetic
morphology made quantitative (Fig.~\texttt{gartner\_4d\_fidelity.png}).

<<tab-gartner>>=
d <- J$gartner
if (is.null(d)) { note_missing("4D-bioprinting (Gartner) maturity") } else {
  d <- as.data.frame(d)
  w <- reshape(d[, c("lineage","sample","score")], idvar = "lineage",
               timevar = "sample", direction = "wide")
  names(w) <- sub("^score\\.", "", names(w))
  ## order columns: manual ('man') then 4D ('r0','r40') when present
  cols <- intersect(c("lineage","man","r0","r40"), names(w))
  w <- w[, cols, drop = FALSE]
  pretty <- c(lineage = "Lineage", man = "Manual (dots)", r0 = "4D r0", r40 = "4D r40 (lines)")
  names(w) <- pretty[names(w)]
  ktab(w, "Conformation-controlled kidney organoids (Gartner 2021/25; \\texttt{figures/gartner\\_results.json}): lineage-maturity projection scores for manual ``dots'' vs 4D-printed ``lines'' (high aspect ratio, r40). The r40 conformation maximises proximal-tubule and podocyte maturity and minimises off-target stroma.",
       "tab:gartner", align = c("l", rep("r", ncol(w) - 1)), digits = 4)
}
@

\subsection{Programmed regulatory logic: synthetic-morphogen states}\label{sec:results-toda}

Projecting Toda et al.\ synNotch-morphogen samples \cite{toda2020} into the Neocortex Atlas
patterns (11{,}068 shared genes), the engineered circuits do not produce noise --- they park
cells in stable, high-score pattern states ($\sim$19{,}000--22{,}000 across patterns 3--7),
and the synNotch ON/OFF toggle moves cells between a growth-like and an arrest-like regime.
This is the empirical content of Davies' ``regulatory module'': an engineered circuit creating
reproducible ``hypergraph states'' that align with primary developmental patterns
(Fig.~\texttt{toda\_morphogenesis\_logic.png}).

\subsection{Effector self-assembly: Anthrobots}\label{sec:results-anthrobot}

The Anthrobot self-assembly transcriptome (90{,}083 cells, two samples \cite{gumuskaya2024})
shows robust activation of the multiciliated-cell program ($FOXJ1$, $DNAI1$) and high
regulatory modularity (\Sexpr{anthro_modules} spectral modules) --- the ``effector/motility'' module: the
$FOXJ1$ regulon (the regulatory layer) successfully driving the formation of motile ciliary
structures (the effector layer) in adult human airway progenitors with no synthetic circuit
(Fig.~\texttt{anthrobot\_motility\_benchmark.png}).

\subsection{Vascularisation and the metabolic wall}\label{sec:results-vorg}

In vascularised cortical organoids (vOrganoids, 57{,}180 cells; vOrg 31{,}851 / Org 25{,}329;
days 65 and 100 \cite{shi2020}) we find clean transcriptomic evidence that vasculature
relieves the hypoxic ``metabolic wall'': Notch-pathway cross-talk regulons are up in
vOrganoids ($RBPJ$ $+0.072$, $p=7.5\times10^{-19}$; $HES5$ $+0.052$, $p=5.6\times10^{-5}$;
$HIF1A$ $+0.042$, $p=5.7\times10^{-8}$) while the chronic-hypoxia regulator $EPAS1$ (HIF-2$\alpha$)
is down ($-0.056$, $p=6.3\times10^{-17}$); endothelial markers $CDH5$/$KDR$/$CLDN5$/$VWF$/$FLT1$/$TIE1$
are detected as expected. (These scores use TF-expression fallback; richer regulon-based
scoring activates when the Pando GRN module table is present on GPU hardware.) The constructive
counterpart --- actually \emph{building} that vasculature rather than waiting for it to
co-emerge --- is now within reach via embedded sacrificial channels \cite{skylarscott2019swift}
and model-guided organ-scale vascular layout fed directly to the bioprinter
\cite{sexton2025vasc}; \S\ref{sec:concl-forward}(iv) proposes pairing it with the Hypergraph
Neural ODE to find the dose at which the relief signal stabilises (Fig.~\texttt{vorganoid\_crosstalk.png}).

\subsection{Self-repair dynamics: Hypergraph Neural ODE}\label{sec:results-regen}

In a mouse kidney ischemia--reperfusion time course (Balzer 2022; 113{,}579 cells; days
0/1/3/14; short and long injury \cite{balzer2022}), a \texttt{LatentHypergraphODE} fitted in
1.2\,s separates the regulatory layers cleanly. \emph{Stable regenerative drivers} (low
rollout MSE --- well-described by the autonomous flow): $Lhx1$ 0.047, $Cdh1$ 0.056, $Pax8$
0.075, $Pax2$ 0.097, $Six2$/$Six1$ $\approx$0.110, $Wt1$ 0.111, $Foxc2$ 0.112. \emph{Dynamic
injury markers} (high MSE --- transient, not captured by an autonomous flow): $Fos$ 4.38,
$Jun$ 1.45, $Cd44$ 0.93, $Atf3$ 0.80. This is exactly the homeostatic-versus-stress split
predicted by a regenerative-flow view --- and the dynamical-systems analogue of the
attractor picture of cell identity \cite{kauffman1969,huang2009}
(Fig.~\texttt{regenerative\_flow.png}).

<<tab-regen>>=
d <- tryCatch(J$regen$ode$per_tf_mse, error = function(e) NULL)
if (is.null(d)) { note_missing("regenerative-flow Hypergraph Neural ODE") } else {
  mse <- unlist(d)
  df <- data.frame(TF = names(mse), `Rollout MSE` = as.numeric(mse), check.names = FALSE)
  df <- df[order(df$`Rollout MSE`), ]
  df$Class <- ifelse(df$`Rollout MSE` < 0.5, "stable regenerative driver", "dynamic injury marker")
  rownames(df) <- NULL
  ktab(df, sprintf("Hypergraph Neural ODE fit to the Balzer 2022 mouse-kidney ischemia--reperfusion time course (\\texttt{figures/regenerative\\_flow\\_results.json}; %s cells, days 0/1/3/14, fit in %.1f\\,s). TFs with low rollout error are well-described by an autonomous flow (homeostatic, structural); high-error TFs are transient stress responders.",
                   num(g(tryCatch(J$regen$n_cells, error=function(e) NULL), 113579)),
                   g(tryCatch(J$regen$ode$elapsed_sec, error=function(e) NULL), 1.2)),
       "tab:regen", align = c("l","r","l"), digits = 3)
}
@

\subsection{Network controllability of the regulome (toward the anatomical compiler)}\label{sec:results-control}

Promoting the diagnostic readouts to a control problem (\S\ref{sec:methods-control}; \texttt{jaxctrl}
on the TF co-regulation graph), we get a first, transcriptome-only pass at the ``anatomical
compiler.'' Two findings stand out.

<<network-control>>=
nc <- J$control
if (is.null(nc)) nc <- load_json(fig("network_control_results.json"))
if (is.null(nc) || isFALSE(nc$jaxctrl) || identical(nc$status, "jaxctrl_unavailable")) {
  cat("\\noindent ", if (is.null(nc)) "" else "(\\texttt{jaxctrl} not available at knit time --- it is a project dependency: \\texttt{uv sync}, then \\texttt{scripts/benchmark\\_network\\_control.py}.) ")
  if (is.null(nc)) note_missing("network controllability (jaxctrl)")
} else {
  ct <- nc$controllability
  cat(sprintf("\\textbf{(1) The master-regulator set is \\emph{not} a controlling input set in the linear sense.} On a sparse TF co-regulation network (%d regulons), the curated %d master regulators (%s) drive a controllability subspace of rank only %d/%d --- consistent with structural-controllability theory, where sparse heterogeneous-degree networks need many driver nodes.\n\n",
              ct$n, ct$n_drivers, paste(nc$driver_tfs, collapse=", "), ct$key_tf_set_rank, ct$n))
  st <- nc$steer_to_target
  if (!is.null(st) && isTRUE(st$available)) {
    ## return bare math content (no surrounding $...$); the template wraps it
    msci <- function(x) {  # 0.36 -> "3.6\\times10^{-1}", 586 -> "5.9\\times10^{2}"
      e <- floor(log10(abs(x) + 1e-300)); sprintf("%.1f\\times10^{%d}", x / 10^e, e)
    }
    fmt_e   <- function(x) if (is.null(x)||length(x)==0||!is.finite(x)) "\\mathrm{undef.}" else if (abs(x) >= 1e4 || (abs(x) > 0 && abs(x) < 1e-2)) msci(x) else sprintf("%.0f", x)
    fmt_lam <- function(x) if (is.null(x)||length(x)==0) "\\mathrm{n/a}" else msci(x)
    lv <- nc$control_leverage_top20  # data.frame (jsonlite simplifyVector) or list-of-lists
    lv_tf <- if (is.data.frame(lv)) lv$tf else vapply(lv, function(e) e$tf, character(1))
    leverage <- paste(utils::head(lv_tf, 5), collapse=", ")
    cat(sprintf("\\textbf{(2) The regulome is steerable with broad actuation but \\emph{not} from the master regulators alone.} Driving the early-pseudotime TF state to the late (mature) state has finite minimum control energy ($\\mathcal{E}^\\star\\approx %s$) under full-TF actuation --- the controllability Gramian is well conditioned ($\\lambda_{\\min}\\approx %s$) --- whereas with only the %d master regulators (or a random %d-TF set) the Gramian is numerically singular ($\\lambda_{\\min}\\approx %s$, i.e.\\ $\\le 0$ to working precision), so $\\mathcal{E}^\\star$ along the unreachable directions is effectively unbounded. Consistently, an LQR feedback law $u=-K(x-x_f)$ on the master-regulator inputs has cost-to-go $%s$ ($\\lVert K\\rVert=%.0f$) versus $%s$ ($\\lVert K\\rVert=%.0f$) with full actuation, and the full-actuation closed loop drives the master TFs ($NEUROD6$, $GLI3$, $FOXG1$, $DLX2$) onto $x_f$ within the horizon (Fig.~\\texttt{network\\_control.png}). The single-input control-leverage ranking is well-behaved (top TFs %s).\n\n",
                fmt_e(st$energy_full_inputs), fmt_lam(st$gramian_min_eig_full), ct$n_drivers, ct$n_drivers, fmt_lam(st$gramian_min_eig_key_tf),
                fmt_e(st$lqr_cost_to_go_key_tf), st$lqr_gain_norm_key_tf, fmt_e(st$lqr_cost_to_go_full), st$lqr_gain_norm_full, leverage))
  }
  cat("\\noindent The lesson is methodological. A \\emph{linear} model on the static co-regulation graph under-rates the master regulators --- they are the privileged handles of the \\emph{nonlinear} flow (\\S\\ref{sec:results-regen}), and the static graph's heavy regulon overlap collapses most directions into a slow, weakly-actuated subspace. So the anatomical-compiler programme (\\S\\ref{sec:concl-forward}) must do optimal control on the learned Hypergraph Neural ODE, not on a linearisation --- which is exactly what \\texttt{jaxctrl}'s differentiable LQR/MPC and \\texttt{diffrax} adjoints make tractable; the script here is the linear warm-up. (\\texttt{figures/network\\_control\\_results.json}; \\texttt{scripts/benchmark\\_network\\_control.py}.)")
}
@

\subsection{Steering a learned regulome to a target: optimal control on the Hypergraph Neural ODE}\label{sec:results-anacomp}

The nonlinear counterpart of the previous section, and the prototype of the anatomical compiler:
fit a Hypergraph Neural ODE to the kidney injury-repair timecourse (\S\ref{sec:results-regen}),
then --- treating that learned ODE as the plant --- compute, by direct shooting through the ODE
(\texttt{diffrax} adjoints + Adam, with the \texttt{jaxctrl} LQR on a linear surrogate as the
warm-start), the actuation schedule on the regenerative-driver TFs that drives the early-injury
state to the recovered (Day-14) state.

<<anatomical-compiler>>=
ac <- J$anacomp
if (is.null(ac)) ac <- load_json(fig("anatomical_compiler_results.json"))
if (is.null(ac) || !identical(ac$status, "ok")) {
  cat("\\noindent ", if (is.null(ac)) "" else "(\\texttt{benchmark\\_anatomical\\_compiler.py} did not complete --- needs hgx + diffrax + jaxctrl + a multi-timepoint h5ad.) ")
  if (is.null(ac)) note_missing("anatomical-compiler optimal control")
} else {
  sc <- ac$surrogate_control; oc <- ac$optimal_control
  tfs <- paste(oc$actuated_tfs, collapse=", ")
  cat(sprintf("On the %d-TF kidney injury panel, the learned ODE's best-fit (regenerative-driver) TFs are \\{%s\\}; we actuate exactly these. A linear surrogate of the learned dynamics nearly interpolates the %s sampled timepoints (relative residual $%.2f$) but is dynamically unstable (max $\\mathrm{Re}\\,\\lambda \\approx %.0f$), so it serves only to warm-start the gain --- the controller is then optimised directly on the nonlinear Hypergraph Neural ODE (a %d-segment piecewise-constant input). The optimised schedule cuts the distance to the target state from %.2f (uncontrolled free rollout) to %.2f overall, and from %.2f to %.2f on the actuated TFs --- a %.0f\\%% reduction on the directly steerable subspace (Fig.~\\texttt{anatomical\\_compiler.png}).\n\n",
              sc$n, tfs, length(ac$timepoints), sc$linear_surrogate_rel_residual, sc$max_re_eig_A,
              oc$n_segments, oc$uncontrolled_final_err, oc$controlled_final_err,
              oc$uncontrolled_final_err_actuated, oc$controlled_final_err_actuated,
              100 * oc$error_reduction_frac_actuated))
  cat("\\noindent This is, deliberately, a minimal proof of the loop: a learned tissue-dynamics model + a target state $\\rightarrow$ an explicit intervention schedule, all differentiable. The same loop with a richer plant (a larger regulome, more timepoints, mechanistically-constrained drift) and richer actuation (the bioprinting / optogenetic / dose handles of \\S\\ref{sec:concl-forward}) is the anatomical-compiler programme. (\\texttt{figures/anatomical\\_compiler\\_results.json}; \\texttt{scripts/benchmark\\_anatomical\\_compiler.py}.)")
}
@

\subsection{Activity-dependent regulome (agency proxy)}\label{sec:results-learn}

As a scRNA-seq proxy for activity-dependent plasticity (the Kagan DishBrain data being
embargoed until 2026-12-31), the Hrvatin V1 light-stimulation dataset (65{,}216 cells; 0/1/4\,h
\cite{hrvatin2018}) reproduces the canonical immediate-early dynamics: IEG module mean
$-0.13 \rightarrow +0.06 \rightarrow -0.07$ (peak at 1\,h: $Fos$, $Fosb$, $Egr1/2$, $Arc$,
$Jun$, $Junb$, $Npas4$), with late-response genes ($Bdnf$, $Homer1$, $Dusp1$, $Rgs2$, $Crem$)
peaking 1--4\,h --- the substrate on which an ``embodied memory / learning'' module would
have to act (Fig.~\texttt{learning\_regulome.png}).

\subsection{Microglia as a maturation module}\label{sec:results-microglia}

Adding iPSC-derived microglia to brain organoids (Park 2023 \cite{park2023}) drives a highly
significant increase in Neocortex-Atlas Pattern 2 (mature neuron) activity (shift $+0.071$,
$p=$\,\Sexpr{park_p_str}); a microglial pruning signature is not significantly changed in the
Favuzzi comparison ($p=0.24$), consistent with the effect being maturation rather than
pruning per se. In the Popova chimeric model \cite{popova2021}, microglia integrated into
organoids reach higher regulatory modularity (up to \Sexpr{popova_max} spectral modules) than in primary
culture (5), evidence that the organoid microenvironment supports the emergence of complex
immune--neural regulatory states --- a ``multiscale holobiont / maturation module'' result
(Figs.~\texttt{microglia\_park\_maturation.png}, \texttt{microglia\_favuzzi\_validation.png}).

\subsection{Module identifiability across systems}\label{sec:results-nitmb}

The Module Identifiability Index (Hodge-Laplacian spectral gap, \S\ref{sec:methods-mii}) orders
systems by how distinct their regulatory modules are (Table~\ref{tab:nitmb}): self-organised
brain organoids and primary fetal kidney maintain the sharpest module structure, and bioprinted
kidney is close behind --- a topological quantification of the ``identifiability'' challenge, and
a way to track how close a biofabricated construct is to a primary-tissue blueprint at the level
of modular organisation (Figs.~\texttt{kidney\_modularity\_hodge.png}, \texttt{nitmb\_modularity\_test.png}).

<<tab-nitmb>>=
d <- J$nitmb
if (is.null(d)) { note_missing("Module Identifiability Index (NITMB)") } else {
  d <- as.data.frame(d)
  names(d) <- c("System", "Module Identifiability Index")
  d <- d[order(-d$`Module Identifiability Index`), ]; rownames(d) <- NULL
  ktab(d, "Module Identifiability Index across self-organised, primary, and bioprinted systems (\\texttt{figures/nitmb\\_modularity\\_report.json}; higher = sharper, more distinct regulatory modules).",
       "tab:nitmb", align = c("l","r"), digits = 3)
}
@

\subsection{Liver master-regulator induction}\label{sec:results-liver}

In 3D-bioprinted human hepatorganoids \cite{zhang2025}, the liver master regulators are robustly
induced relative to 2D hiHeps (Table~\ref{tab:liver}) --- the same ``3D context induces the right
regulatory program'' signal seen in brain and kidney, in a third organ system
(Fig.~\texttt{liver\_fidelity\_zhang.png}).

<<tab-liver>>=
d <- J$liver
if (is.null(d)) { note_missing("liver hepatorganoid master-regulator induction") } else {
  d <- as.data.frame(d)
  d$p_val <- vapply(d$p_val, fmt_p, character(1))
  names(d) <- c("Master regulator", "Mean $\\log_2$FC (3D HHO vs 2D hiHep)", "$p$", "$n$ targets")
  ktab(d, "3D-bioprinted human hepatorganoid (HHO) regulon induction relative to 2D hiHeps (\\texttt{figures/liver\\_fidelity\\_results.json}).",
       "tab:liver", align = c("l","r","r","r"), digits = 2)
}
@

%==============================================================================
\section{Conclusions and Outlook}\label{sec:conclusions}
%==============================================================================

\subsection{What the modeling demonstrates}\label{sec:concl-demonstrates}

Taken together, these results establish four things. (1) \emph{A higher-order network
framework can be both fast and faithful}: \hgx\ matches published HGNN accuracy, reproduces
all five biological checks of a published organoid regulome, and runs inference one to two
orders of magnitude faster than existing implementations --- fast enough to be a routine
analysis tool rather than a one-off. (2) \emph{Organoid regulomes encode conserved human
regulatory logic}: their topology predicts CRISPRi outcomes in primary human cortex with
high direction concordance, conservation rises monotonically as the test system becomes more
tissue-like, and key regulons are conserved to marmoset and mouse --- empirical support for
the GRN-kernel view of development. (3) \emph{The organoid fidelity gap is specific,
locatable, and bioengineerable}: it sits in the mature, layer-specific, human-specific
programs (Neocortex-Atlas Pattern 2; the oRG and synaptic patterns), it has a regulatory
correlate (the Early-Stage Buffer --- early master regulators depleted for mature disease
genes), and 3D/4D bioprinting closes much of it --- roughly tenfold gains in synaptic and
oRG pattern activity, a 3.2-fold gain in proximal-tubule maturity, $>1.8\;\log_2\!\mathrm{FC}$
induction of liver master regulators. (4) \emph{The same instruments measure organisation
itself}: the Hodge-Laplacian Module Identifiability Index ranks systems by modular distinctness
and tracks biofabricated constructs converging toward primary tissue, and the Hypergraph
Neural ODE decomposes a regulome into stable structural drivers versus transient stress
markers --- a decomposition that is, by construction, also a way to ask how far a tissue's
modular organisation has degraded (the link to the tissue-organisation and attractor views of
cancer).

\subsection{Limitations}\label{sec:concl-limits}

Several of the engineered-system tracks currently score against TF expression rather than the
full Pando regulon table (which is large and GPU-resident); cross-validation is not yet
applied uniformly across analyses; the persistent-homology summaries are computed on
subsampled hypergraphs; the THNNConv overflow fix is diagnosed but not yet merged into \hgx\
core; and the ``agency'' track uses an activity-induced scRNA-seq proxy rather than the
embargoed in-vitro-learning data. None of these affect the headline comparisons, but they
bound the strength of the higher-order-specific claims.

\subsection{Pushing the technology forward: a programme of new experiments}\label{sec:concl-forward}

The natural next step is to close the loop --- to use \hgx, its Module Identifiability Index,
its Hypergraph Neural ODE, and its CellFlow-based simulation-based inference not just to
\emph{score} engineered tissues after the fact but to \emph{design} the next round. Stated
abstractly, every item below is one \emph{optimal-control} problem on the Hypergraph Neural ODE:
given a target tissue state $x_f$ (a primary-tissue pattern profile, a mature-driver
configuration), find the actuation $u(t)$ --- print geometry, synNotch input, light schedule,
microglia/vasculature dose, bioelectric set-point --- that drives $x_0 \to x_f$ with minimum
cost, subject to what is physically actuatable. \texttt{jaxctrl}'s differentiable controllers
(controllability Gramians, structural driver-node analysis, LQR, and MPC via \texttt{diffrax}
adjoints) supply the solver; \S\ref{sec:results-control} is the linear warm-up (showing the
actuation must act on the nonlinear flow, not a linearisation), and \S\ref{sec:results-anacomp}
is the first end-to-end instance --- a learned regulome ODE plus a target state yielding an explicit
TF-actuation schedule. This is what Levin calls the \emph{anatomical compiler}
\cite{pezzulo2016,levin2022tame}, and the experiments below scale it up with richer plants and
actuators. Concretely:

\paragraph{(i) A 4D-bioprinting maturation assay with a model-in-the-loop.}
The Gartner-style conformation sweep showed maturity scaling with print geometry; run a
denser sweep (aspect ratio, curvature, packing, matrix stress-relaxation rate) with \hgx\
pattern-projection and the Identifiability Index as the live readout, and let an
optimiser (Bayesian / evolutionary, as in the xenobot design pipeline \cite{kriegman2020})
propose the next geometry. The deliverable is a \emph{design map}: which physical parameters
move which mature regulatory programs, for brain, kidney, and liver constructs. This is now
practicable: FRESH-style freeform embedding lets one print collagen types I/II/III at tissue
resolution \cite{lee2019fresh,moss2025fresh}, perfusable internal channels (CHIPS) keep
organ-scale constructs alive in a bioreactor \cite{shiwarski2025chips}, embedded sacrificial
vascular networks (SWIFT) reach high cellular density \cite{skylarscott2019swift}, and
model-guided algorithms can lay out organ-scale synthetic vasculature for the printer in
minutes \cite{sexton2025vasc} --- the wet-lab analogue of the design loop above. Low-cost,
open-source direct-ink-writing platforms (PRINTESS \cite{printess2025}; and the broader
open-hardware effort led from the Feinberg/Shiwarski groups) make running the sweep at the
scale of dozens of conditions realistic; the corresponding lab operates a FRESH collagen
bioprinter and a locally-built PRINTESS, so the model-in-the-loop assay is the immediate next
step rather than an aspiration.

\paragraph{(ii) Hybrid programmed-plus-printed tissues.}
Combine a synNotch / synthetic-morphogen circuit \cite{morsut2016,toda2018,toda2020}
(the regulatory module) with bioprinted geometry (the scaffold module) and ask whether the
two together hit a primary-tissue pattern state that neither reaches alone --- using the
``hypergraph state'' alignment of \S\ref{sec:results-toda} as the target metric and the
ODE driver-stability of \S\ref{sec:results-regen} to check the state is an attractor, not a
transient. This is a direct experimental attack on Sol\'e's ``synthetic developmental
programs / predictable design'' open problem.

\paragraph{(iii) Optogenetic morphogenesis with a transcriptomic readout.}
Light-gated control of WNT (or SHH, BMP) lets one impose a designed signalling schedule;
pair it with single-cell readout and use the Hodge-Laplacian stop-signal detector to find
the modularity threshold at which the construct ``commits'' to maturation, then test whether
holding the schedule at that threshold improves Pattern-2 activity. This turns the
``sensor/feedback'' module from a descriptive label into a controllable variable.

\paragraph{(iv) A microglia (and vasculature) titration series.}
Park and Popova showed microglia act as a maturation module; titrate microglia (and,
separately, engineered vasculature, building on the vOrganoid metabolic-wall result) into
brain organoids across a dose series and fit the Hypergraph Neural ODE to the resulting time
course --- the prediction is that there is a dose at which mature drivers ($SATB2$, $BCL11B$,
synaptic genes) cross from ``dynamic marker'' into ``stable driver,'' i.e.\ become part of
the construct's attractor. That dose is the engineering target.

\paragraph{(v) A bioelectric layer.}
Following the morphogenetic-information programme \cite{levin2014,levin2018bioelectriccode,pezzulo2016,levin2021bioelectric},
manipulate resting potential / gap-junctional coupling in an organoid or printed construct
and read out the regulome; if the bioelectric state is genuinely a control layer above
transcription, the Identifiability Index and the ODE driver set should shift predictably.
This is the cleanest available test of whether ``agential materials'' can be steered at the
tissue level with a non-genetic knob.

\paragraph{(vi) A cancer-as-loss-of-module-identifiability assay.}
Finally, the inverse experiment: take a graded series from primary tissue $\rightarrow$
organoid $\rightarrow$ tumour organoid $\rightarrow$ established cancer line, and show that
the Module Identifiability Index falls, the ODE driver set collapses (homeostatic regulators
moving from ``stable'' to ``unconstrained''), and the unicellular-vs-multicellular gene
balance shifts \cite{trigos2017} --- operationalising the tissue-organisation \cite{soto2011},
atavism \cite{davies2011metazoa}, and attractor \cite{huang2009} views of cancer on the same
footing as the synthetic-tissue benchmarks, and giving differentiation-/adaptive-therapy
programmes \cite{gatenby2009,montagud2022} a higher-order-network target to steer toward.

The throughline is the one Davies stated in 2008 \cite{davies2008} and Sol\'e et al.\
restated in 2024 \cite{sole2024}: the genotype--phenotype map for multicellular form is
nonlinear and emergent, so progress comes less from micromanaging molecules than from
building tissues with the materials' own competencies \emph{and} from having instruments
sharp enough to tell, quantitatively, when the program has been executed. This work
contributes the instrument; the programme above is what we propose to do with it.

